someone in an assistive
device was leaving the venue.

00:18:27.348 --> 00:18:30.241
Also, stairs, escalators, elevators

00:18:30.308 --> 00:18:33.486
in relation to conference rooms,
dining area,

00:18:33.487 --> 00:18:38.292
sponsor hall, and your hotel rooms.

00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:43.963
Also, the speaker spaces,
stage heights,

00:18:43.964 --> 00:18:46.065
how the chairs were being laid out,

00:18:46.066 --> 00:18:49.716
the aisleways,
things of that nature, lighting.

00:18:51.238 --> 00:18:54.741
In terms of the hotel,
we also toured the hotel

00:18:54.742 --> 00:18:58.233
with the representative
from the event space.

00:18:58.812 --> 00:19:00.813
This hotel had accessible rooms,

00:19:00.814 --> 00:19:04.284
so we looked at the variety
of accessibility rooms,

00:19:04.285 --> 00:19:07.388
and it impacted
how we made decisions.

00:19:07.922 --> 00:19:10.957
In terms of wayfinding
for your events,

00:19:10.958 --> 00:19:16.263
always provide basic,
simple maps and signage.

00:19:17.231 --> 00:19:21.435
I would say avoid
venue-provided or "designed"

00:19:22.836 --> 00:19:26.072
pieces that the venue may provide.

00:19:26.073 --> 00:19:27.807
One of the things
I remember about WordCamp

00:19:27.808 --> 00:19:31.077
US and National Harbor
was that the information

00:19:31.078 --> 00:19:33.012
that they provided was "designed"

00:19:33.013 --> 00:19:37.785
so that meant there were tiny
light gray-type colors

00:19:39.586 --> 00:19:43.145
that had color contrast issues,
et cetera, et cetera.

00:19:43.146 --> 00:19:46.292
I basically recreated
some of the maps,

00:19:46.293 --> 00:19:48.761
which I'll show you in a second.

00:19:48.762 --> 00:19:50.730
Provide wayfinding
in multiple formats.

00:19:50.731 --> 00:19:53.933
Again, most WordCamps
have a map of the venue,

00:19:53.934 --> 00:19:58.932
but it's a graphic like a JPEG
or a PDF, which isn't accessible.

00:20:01.742 --> 00:20:03.509
Provide it in multiple formats,

00:20:03.510 --> 00:20:07.180
and I'll talk a little bit
about that in a second.

00:20:07.181 --> 00:20:10.984
One thing that I did,
and I think it may have been a first,

00:20:10.985 --> 00:20:12.485
was to offer common path maps

00:20:12.486 --> 00:20:15.422
and descriptions to key event spaces.

00:20:16.156 --> 00:20:21.294
I'll talk about that in a second,
but also, please place clear,

00:20:21.295 --> 00:20:24.330
concise signage at key areas

00:20:24.331 --> 00:20:26.667
and spots along common path.

00:20:30.604 --> 00:20:33.272
This is an example
of a common path map that I did.

00:20:33.273 --> 00:20:36.275
I took a lot of the printed
brochures that they provided to us

00:20:36.276 --> 00:20:40.881
as an organizing team,
and I redrew maps,

00:20:41.081 --> 00:20:45.852
and I listed the common
pathways for our event,

00:20:45.853 --> 00:20:49.422
entering the building to get
to the registration desk,

00:20:49.423 --> 00:20:51.424
from the registration
desk to your room,

00:20:51.425 --> 00:20:54.227
from your room
to the conference space,

00:20:54.228 --> 00:20:56.496
from your room to the dining room,

00:20:56.497 --> 00:20:59.298
from your room to the sponsor area.

00:20:59.299 --> 00:21:02.502
I provided that in
a visual format, but also,

00:21:02.503 --> 00:21:04.771
one of our team members was blind.

